@node "Intro" "Introduction"


                               Introduction



 Thank you for purchasing PageMonster!  We at CultureShock Multimedia have
labored long an hard to bring to the Amiga community the most powerful and
easy Web  page creation environment ever. 


 This is not another text editor, but an environment  designed to construct
Cyberspace like it has never been constructed before.  
 
 In the best  tradition of Amiga based programing and advanced software
design, PageMonster will  harness your existing software library for Web
page construction.   

 For example: if you have an image that requires cropping, or text which
requires  editing, PageMonster will call your favorite paint package or text
editor from within  PageMonster and allow you to edit your file and preview
it before insertion it into your Web project.

 PageMonster also has pre-formatted page designs, forms, tables, background
graphics, background sounds, inline images, multimedia links, external
links,  and more, all just a few mouse clicks from becoming finished code.

We, at CultureShock Multimedia, believe, like many others, that the Internet
is a  very important part of the planet's future. Like the Amiga System
itself, innovative  software and superior technology should be accessible to
all who wish to participate,  not merely those who can afford to.  

It is in this spirit that PageMonster was conceived.  We hope you enjoy  our
program and we look forward to visiting your new Web site. 

 Please register your purchase with us.  In future, we intend to support
FRAMES, VRML, DYNAMIC HTML and other Web page innovations.   Your
registration number will allow you download free plugins and revisions from
our @{"PageMonster Online  Support" system "execute Pagemonster:scripts/onlineb.scpt"} Page.



 @{"Return To Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"

                              INSTALLATION


             Installing the AVPlayer & other required files

 There are a four public domain files you will need to install in your
system before PageMonster will operate.  The following information is basic
to the use of the Amiga OS.  The information is common place  to experienced
Amiga users, but here are step by step instructions for new Amiga users. 

  Since PageMonster was created using the AmigaVision Professional Authoring
Program, the AmigaVision Player needs to be in your 'C:'directory and the
AmigaVision libraries need to be put in your system's 'libs:' directory.

  Lastly, the command 'Append' must also be added to your system's 'C:'
directory. 
 
              Download 'avplay_2.4.lzh' from Aminet at:  

   http://wuarchive.wustl.edu/pub/aminet/info/www/dirs/aminet/gfx/show/
   avplay_2.4.lzh


  'Append' can be found in the Fred Archive on fish disk 'FF379' or at:

       http://www.funet.fi/pub/amiga/fish/301-400/ff379/Append.lha

   You can find links to these archives on our DOWNLOAD PAGE located at:

            http://atozweb.com/zipperware/pmdownload.html

  
                               STEP 1

  Copy these files to the 'ram:' directory.  At the workbench, double click
the workbench icon with the left mouse button.  In the workbench window,
find the 'system' drawer and double click to open it.  Find the 'shell' icon
and double click it with left mouse button.  At the command line enter: 

                    'LHA e,x ram:AV_Play.lzh ram:' 

 Press the 'enter' key and the file AV_Play.lzh will decompress.  Now
decompress the Append command by typing, 

         'LHA e,x ram:Append.lha' and press the 'enter' key.


                               STEP 2

  At the Workbench, open the 'RAM DISK' icon by double clicking with the
left mouse button on its icon.  Then, under the 'WINDOW' pull down menu,
select SHOW and then ALL FILES.  If you've decompressed the archives
properly, you should see the icons representing the files.


                               STEP 3

  Next at the Workbench, open the System: partition by double clicking on
its icon. (Your System partition is where your system directories are
located. (Your system partition is usually referred to as 'Workbench:' or
'DH0:', although your system may differ.)  Be sure that the 'SHOW ALL FILES'
switch in step 2 is still selected.  Find the directory icon labeled C and
open it. (double click with the left mouse button)   

                               
                               STEP 4

  Grab the AVPlayer icon from the 'RAM DISK' window and drag it into the 'C'
directory's window.


                               STEP 5

  In your System Partition find the directory icon labeled  'LIBS' and open
it.  In the 'RAM DISK' window, hold the 'shift' key down and using the left
mouse button, select the icons for the 'avbd.library', the
'avtextgad.library', 'camd.library' and the 'realtimelibrary'.  Drag and
drop these icons into the 'LIBS' directory  window.


                               STEP 6

  In the 'RAM DISK' window open the 'Append' drawer icon.  Select the file
named 'APPEND.ENGLISH' by single clicking on the icon.  With the icon
selected, pull down 'rename' from the 'Icons' menu. Rename the file to
'APPEND' (delete the '.ENGLISH') and then drag and drop it in the 'C'
directory's window.  If you followed the above steps correctly you now have
all the files installed required to run PageMonster.


                      NOW INSTALL PAGEMONSTER 1.0

  Okay, that was the hard part.  The installation process should be smooth
sailing from here on out. All you have to do now is run the Installer script
located on the disk labeled 'INSTALL DISK/BGPLUGIN' included with the
PageMonster disk distribution. Just run it by clicking on the
INSTALL_PAGEMONSTER icon, say YES to everything and then REBOOT your
computer, so that PageMonster's assigns can be entered into your system.
PageMonster will be available after reboot.


 @{"Return to Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Config" "Configuration Screen"
                        

                         THE CONFIGURATION SCREEN



  The Configuration screen is where you set up the PageMonster.   It is
these programs and their storage paths that the PageMonster will use to
create your Web  pages.  

In addition, the Web addresses or URLs that you indicate here will be the
URLs  that will be written into your links in the pages you create.

 WEB PAGE ADDRESS

   Put the address of the Web site whose project you are
   creating for here.  Be sure  to put the complete address which should 
   start with, "http://......"

 SAVE SETUP         

   Hit this button after you have entered all your configuration
   information and all  your settings will be saved by PageMonster.

 SET COMMAND         

   This is one of PageMonster's advanced features. It can only be used
   by the AWEB browser. In this area can be set any command which you wish
   to be executed.
   If  SET COMMAND is set to "ON," the command appearing in the command
   field will be referenced when calling the GET LINKS operation in the
   PARAGRAPH MODULE, when loading an INLINE IMAGE in the MEDIA MODULE, 
   and when using the linked list function in the LIST MODULE.

 BROWSER         

   This is where your Amiga browser is located in your system.
   Currently,  PageMonster supports Ibrowse®, AWeb-II®, Amosaic, and any 
   other Amiga browser  which will allow you to open local HTML files
   as arguments.

 TEXT EDITOR 

   Enter the location of your favorite Amiga ascii text editor here.
   PageMonster will  access it when ever you want to manually adjust the 
   code or type in text. (Default is 'C:Ed')

 VIEWER         

   Enter the location of your graphic viewer.  The default is set to
   utilities/multiview.   You can replace this with the location of 
   another viewer we recommend you place it in  your C: directory.

 PLAYER        

   Enter the location of your audio sample player.  The default is set
   to "c:play16."   You can replace this with the location of another
   player.  We recommend you place it in  your C: directory.

 MOD PLAYER

   Enter the location of your mod player.  The default is set to
   "c:tinyplayer."  You  can replace this with the location of another mod
   player.  We recommend you place it in  your C: directory. 
 
 PAINT PROGRAM

   Enter the location of your paint program.  The default is set
   to  ImageFX:imageFX®.  You can replace this with the location of another
   paint program.   Deluxe Paint®, Brilliance® and PPaint® are some
   of the many programs that  PageMonster can access when you require it.  

   Note:  These applications are accessed by PageMonster through the CLI.  
          In some  cases, PageMonster needs the application to open a 
          particular file, so that an option  must be entered into the 
          configuration along with the path to the application.  

          For  example, if you are using DeluxePaintV® you must add an 
          option of -f after the path  name on the CONFIGURATION SCREEN 
          before saving the settings. 

 DEFAULT DIR

   This is the path in your storage area (HARD DRIVE) that
   PageMonster's  requestors will go to first.  On setup, PageMonster
   defaults to a subdirectory in the PageMonster directory, but
   you may wish to create a separate directory elsewhere.

 PAGE STORAGE        

   This is where PageMonster writes it's backup files.  This
   backup allows you to  exit and enter the PageMonster while working on a
   particular project.  All your files and  their address paths will be 
   intact so you can continue to edit your pages without having  to reset 
   all your paths. 

   Note:  The @{"BACKUP" link "MMenu" 124} feature on the MAIN SCREEN is a powerful multi-level
          backup  system.  Please read the documentation on the @{"MAIN SCREEN" link "MMenu" 95}

          regarding the BACKUP  feature.

 FORM ACTION        

   This is HTML tag that calls the CGI script on a server.  The
   CGI script takes the  information entered in the form area and sends it
   to  the EMail address indicated in the EMAIL field.  
   To  utilize this feature, you should  contact your server's web master
   or administrator for the  correct URL to the CGI directory and the
   mailform script. 

 DOMAIN NAME 

   Enter the domain name of the Web site that you are creating.

 EMAIL         

   Enter your Email address. This will be used later by the PageMonster
   as a mailto in the INTERNET LINK menu and the feedback address 
   of the FORMS MODULE.

 SPEECH        

   Select this button to utilize PageMonster's on line voice help.

 DIGITIZED

   If you've downloaded the PageMonster's voice files, this
   selection allows you use  those files rather than the synthesizer's.
   
   Note:  Initially, the voice help should help to prompt you through
          PageMonster the first  few times.  After you become comfortable
          with PageMonster you can leave the  SPEECH option off.  When 
          returning to the CONFIGURATION SCREEN,  the SPEECH  option
          automatically goes off.

 COMMAND        

   This is the SET COMMAND on/off switch.

 START PAGEMONSTER 1.0        

   This begins PageMonster.

 ABOUT         

   This is some information about us at CultureShock Multimedia.

 HELP         

   Select this to go to online help.


 @{"Return to Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "MMenu" "The Main Menu "
  

                              THE MAIN MENU


 The MAIN MENU is the first screen after you've started PageMonster.  From
this  screen all other screens are accessible.  You will begin to build each
module of your  Web project by going to that screen, creating the module and
returning to the MAIN  MENU in order to assemble the completed project.

 SET BACKGROUND         

   Select SET BACKGROUND to go to the @{"BACKGROUND GENERATOR" link "Background" 0}
   PLUGIN  screen to set the background color, texture, background 
   sound, text color, link color and vlink (after you've the link text has
   been selected) color and/or text color.

 TITLE 

   Select TITLE to go to the @{"TITLE MODULE" link "Title" 0} and create the title for your
   project. This the line of text that is visible on the URL address line
   when someone is at  your page.

 HEADER         

   Select HEADER to go to the @{"HEADER MODULE" link "header" 0} where you can create
   headers  (headlines) for your page.  The different settings from H1 to 
   H4 indicate the different  size of font that each browser program will
   see. This is set by each browser.  The constant factor is that H1 
   is the largest,while each setting that follows is smaller down to  H4, 
   the smallest header.


 MEDIA LINKS         

   Select MEDIA LINKS to go to the @{"MEDIA MODULE" link "Media" 0} where you can
   create, edit   and insert sound, pictures, internal and external links,
   edit graphics, create and store  links and preview these elements.
   This section is quite extensive and the area which adds sophistication
   to your Web sites. 

 PARAGRAPH 

   Select PARAGRAPH to go the @{"PARAGRAPH MODULE" link "paragraph" 0} where you can  load
   pre-formatted text or type in text.  There are some word processing
   features and  you can go to the text editor that you set in the
   @{"CONFIGURATION SCREEN" link "Config" 42} by clicking on the CODE WINDOW.
   Text links which you  created in the @{"MEDIA MODULE" link "Media" 0} 
   are connected to text here.  

 LISTS 

   Select @{"LISTS" link "List" 0} when you want to enter a list of items, ordered or
   unordered, bullated or numbered. Linked or unlinked.

 FORMS 

   Select @{"FORMS" link "Forms" 0} to choose pre-formatted forms, create catalogs, order
   forms and  questionnaires.

 EDIT MODE 

   Select the EDIT MODE button to toggle between EDIT and ASSEMBLY
   MODE.   The power of PageMonster allows you to edit, re-edit, assemble
   and re-assemble until  you are satisfied and finally save your project. 

 PREVIEW 

   Select PREVIEW when you want to see what you have created with the
   code appearing in the @{"CODE WINDOW" link "notes" 27} on the main screen.  There are PREVIEW
   buttons on  various screens in PageMonster.  Each PREVIEW button will 
   call your @{"browser" link "Config" 35} and display the page elements created by the code 
   displayed in the current CODE WINDOW  on that particular screen.
 
 RESET 

   Selecting RESET will do different functions depending upon the
   combination of  buttons selected.  Selecting RESET in the MAIN MENU
   brings up a requestor which allows you the choices to: - update the
   current code in the CODE WINDOW - clear the current code on the
   MAIN MENU - delete a file stored in ram modules. - do global clear to
   remove all files- clear stored code in the BACKUP area of storage

 INDEX

   Selecting INDEX will open the @{"INDEX MODULE" link "Index" 0}. This function is
   utilized to create a main index for pages previously
   created by the PageMonster.  

 HRULE         

   Selecting HRULE will insert a horizontal line into your Web
   page. You may select either a GRAPHIC or PLAIN rule.

 B1 

   Selecting B1 will activate the B1 Page Buffer.  Selecting BACKUP now
   will store  the  code in the CODE WINDOW.  To clear the B1 buffer, 
   select B1 and select RESET. You can recall this code by selecting 
   B1 and selecting INSERT.

 B2 

   Selecting B2 will activate the B2 Page Buffer.  Selecting BACKUP now
   will store  the  code in the CODE WINDOW.  To clear the B2 buffer, 
   select B2 and select RESET.   
   You can recall this code by selecting B2 and selecting INSERT.

 B3         

   Selecting B3 will activate the B3 Page Buffer.  Selecting BACKUP now
   will store  the  code in the CODE WINDOW.  To clear the B3 buffer, 
   select B3 and select RESET.
   You can recall this code by selecting B3 and selecting INSERT.  

 INSERT         

   INSERT will put stored code into the CODE WINDOW.  What is actually
   inserted  depends upon what other selections have been chosen.  If B1 
   is  selected, INSERT will  put the code stored in the B1 PAGE BUFFER 
   into the CODE WINDOW. 
   The same is  true for B2, B3, and/or BACKUP.                

 BACKUP 

   Selecting BACKUP alone will backup your current project including
   all modules  (TITLE, HEADER, MEDIA LINKS, PARAGRAPH, LISTS AND FORMS).
   When a buffer  (B1, B2, and/or B3) is selected, then BACKUP will append
   the code in the CODE WINDOW to the selected buffer.

 LOAD 

   Selecting LOAD when in EDIT MODE will go to a requester where you can
   reload a PageMonster project to re-edit.  If LOAD is selected in 
   ASSEMBLY MODE the  pre-formatted page DESIGN STYLES requester appears.
   You can then select a style.   PageMonster will complete your Web page
   in the style of your choice.

 SAVE 

   Selecting SAVE will bring you to the @{"EXPORT PROJECT MODULE" link "Export" 0} where you
   can save  your completed project and upload your new pages to your Web
   Server.

 CONFIG 

   Selecting CONFIG will return you to the @{"CONFIGURATION SCREEN" link "Config" 0}  where
   you  adjust your configuration.

 PLUGIN 

   Selecting @{"PLUGIN" link "Plug-in" 0} will bring you to a requester to choose a plugin
   file such as the  BACKGROUND or TABLES plugin module.  The PLUGIN button
   is a gateway to future  expansion for PageMonster.  Besides future
   plugin modules forth coming from CultureShock Multimedia, the PLUGIN 
   selection can be used to run any executable file.  Plugin  modules 
   can be written by users in Arexx®, Amiga Dos®, C and AmigaVision®.

 EXIT 

   Select EXIT to close PageMonster.

 HELP

   Select HELP to receive online help.


 @{"Return to Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Background" "The Background Module"
       

                         
                          THE BACKGROUND MODULE




 The BACKGROUND MODULE IS WHERE YOU CAN:

                       -Load a background image 
                       -Load a background sound
                       -View the Image/Hear your sound
                       -Load a background texture

 LOAD IMAGE

   Select this button to tell PageMonster to load an image for your page's
   background.  After selecting your image, choose the correct filetype
   extension for your image.  

   Note:  If you choose the wrong extenstion your background image
          will not load.

 VIEW

   Select here to see your image
 
 BGSOUND

   Select here to load a sound sample.          

 PLAY

   Play the background sound

 ACCEPT

   When all your selections have been made, this will take you back to the
   MAIN MENU.

 CANCEL

   This selection will take you back to the MAIN MENU without any 
   background information

 BACKGROUND COLORS 

   This a list of background colors.  Select your color, then where you 
   want to use it.  (BACKGROUND, TEXT, LINK AND VLINK.)

 BACKGROUND

   Choose a color then choose here to make the background that color.

 TEXT

   Choose a color then this button to make the page text this color.

 LINK
 
   Choose a color then this button to make the text link this color.

 VLINK

   Choose a color then this button to make the choose links this color.

 BG BUFFER

   Select a pre-formatted texture or load a custom background of you 
   making. You can create a custom background and store these settings
   in the five buffer areas.

 CHANGE

   When you turn the CHANGE button ON and select an IMAGE number 
   (1 through 5) you can load a background JPG image to be stored in that
   buffer for future use.  Your background image is repeated on your page,
   so a small image is usually best to create a textured look.


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Title" "THe Title Module"


                             THE TITLE MODULE



The TITLE MODULE allows you to title your page.  There are two windows here.
The larger window is the code window, it shows the current Title code, while
the smaller window is the TEXT ENTRY LINE where you type the title of the
page you are creating.  Be sure to hit the RETURN key after you enter the
title.  

 WRITE         

   This button, when selected, will add an additional title line to the
   code window  when you select ADD.

 ADD 

   This well enter your title into the code window.

 RESET         
  
   Selecting RESET will remove the code in the code window allowing  you
   to start over. 

 MAIN MENU         

   Selecting MAIN MENU returns you to the MAIN MENU

 HELP        

   Gives you Online help


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "header" "THE HEADER MODULE"



                            THE HEADER MODULE


The HEADER MODULE is where the code for your page header is created. The
code window at the top is where your code will appear.  The four header
buttons are used to set the header size, and the text entry window is where
you enter your page  header text.

   NOTE: The actual size of these headers is determained by the Browser's
         setting,  but the relative sizes will be consistant.

 HEADER 1 

   Select HEADER 1 for the largest preset font.

 HEADER 2 

   Select HEADER 2 for the second largest preset font. 

 HEADER 3

   Select HEADER 3 for the third largest preset font.

 HEADER 4 

   Select HEADER 1 for smallest preset font.

 RESET         

   Click here to clear and reset the HEADER CODE WINDOW.

 CENTER 

   Select CENTER to center the header prior to selecting ADD.

 ADD 
   
   Selecting ADD will insert the code in to the HEADER CODE WINDOW.

 MAIN MENU 

   Select here to return to the MAIN MENU

 HELP 

   Select here to go to Online Help.

 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Media" "The Media Module"



                             THE MEDIA MODULE



 The Media Module is where you will create the multimedia components of your
project.  It is in the MEDIA MODULE that you can create and edit  in-line
images, sample sound, run arexx macros rename files and create a list of
links.

 CODE WINDOW 

   The code that you build will appear in this window.  As on any
   PageMonster screen that  has a CODE WINDOW, at any time, you can
   manually.  click in the CODE WINDOW and  edit that code in your 
   @{"configured text editor" link "Config" 42}.  After editing the code, save the file and 
   exit  the editor.

 PAINT PROGRAM

   Select here to go to your @{"configured paint program" link "Config" 66}.  

 RECORD SAMPLE 

   Select RECORD SAMPLE to go to access the @{"RECORD SAMPLE MENU." link "Other" 8}

 AREXX 

   Select @{"AREXX" link "Other" 35} to run an AREXX script.  Arexx links provide incredible
   power and versatility to PageMonster.


 RENAME FILE

   Select RENAME FILE to rename a file which has been incorrectly
   named.  

    Note:  PageMonster assembles Web Page information in it's own 
           proprietary structure  which in many cases means that your
           original file names are changed to fit into PageMonster's 
           design structure.  If PageMonster has made an incorrect
           assumption you may have to manually correct this error and
           rename the file.

 TEXT ENTRY LINE 

   Lines of code will appear here prior to being added to the
   CODE WINDOW.  Should you need to edit the line, you can do so here.

 CENTER 

   When creating an image entry, selecting CENTER prior to selecting
   ADD will center  your image on the Web Page.

 ADD

   Selecting ADD will move the code from the TEXT ENTRY line into the
   CODE WINDOW.

 INLINE IMAGE 

   An Inline image is an image that is on your Web page as opposed to an
   image which is  open outside of your Web page, which is known
   as an EXTERNAL FILE.  To load your  images, select the INLINE IMAGE
   button. A requester will appear select an image file, In the pop up 
   menu select an extension.  The extension tells the Web browser
   what type of file is being downloaded, and more importantly what viewer
   to use to view the file. 
   
   If you have prepared your files complete with  the correct extension, 
   then you should select NONE from the SELECT EXTENSION requester, 
   other wise, select the correct extension. 

 DIRECTORY 

   This selection is an advanced feature of PageMonster. 
   When creating a suite of pages with PageMonster, the DIRECTORY 
   selection is used to link INLINE IMAGES with other PageMonster 
   created pages.  PageMonster's page structure is proprietary, so that 
   pages created with it can easily be incorporated into page suites.  
   
   In short: You can join together many pages using PageMonster.
   just by building them first and then loading them as sub directories
   of the current project (See also: @{"THE INDEX MENU" link "Index" 0} )  
   
 EXTERNAL FILE

   Selecting EXTERNAL FILE brings up a requester where you can select a
   file which will be executed outside of the browser.  When this
   file is chosen on the Web page, an external program is launched which 
   shows this file. 

 @{"INTERNET LINK" link "Other" 90}

    This selection allows you to set a link which will go to another URL 
    on the Internet.

 ALIGNMENT 

   These selections are used with the INLINE IMAGE selection.
   Setting the alignment will dictate where the text will appear in 
   relation to the image.

 @{"COMMAND" link "Other" 143} 

   This selection is a special feature of AWEB-II® which allows
   commands to be executed through the AWEB-II® browser.  If you are using
   AWEB-II® see the manual for its use.  An example of it's use with
   PageMonster is that when previewing an image through the AWEB-II® 
   browser, clicking on that image will load it into the configured paint
   program for realtime editing. 

 MAIN MENU 

   Selecting MAIN MENU will return you to the Main Menu screen.  Any
   code that you have created in the MEDIA MODULE is stored in the 
   MEDIA LINKS buffer and can be put into the MAIN MENU's CODE WINDOW
   by selecting the MEDIA MODULE when in ASSEMBLY MODE.



 @{"VIEW/PLAY" link "Other" 164}

   This selection allows you to see an image and play a sound
   sample prior to actually creating code.  Your viewer and player must be
   configured in order for this function to operate.  The "I" stands for
   Image,  while the "E" stands for external.

 @{"STORE LINK" link "Other" 195} 

   This selection is used in concert with EXTERNAL FILE and/or INTERNET
   LINK.  The external file or Internet link you select is stored in a
   link buffer which can be called in the PARAGRAPH  and LIST MODULES. 
   First select an external file, then select STORE LINK.  The ASSIGN LINKS
   MODULE will appear where you must choose a buffer slot.  Select RETURN 
   get back to the MEDIA MODULE in order to select another external or 
   Internet link file.

 PREVIEW 

   Select PREVIEW when you want to see what you have created with
   the code appearing in the CODE WINDOW on the main screen.  There are
   PREVIEW buttons on various screens in PageMonster.  Each PREVIEW button
   will call your browser and display the page elements created by the code
   displayed in the current CODE WINDOW on that particular screen.

 HELP

   Select here to go to Online Help.


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "paragraph" "The Paragraph Module"
      

                           THE PARAGRAPH MODULE



The Paragraph module is where you enter the main content of your web  page.
The  easiest way to use the paragraph module is to simply enter your text on
the TEXT ENTRY LINE, pressing return after each line.

  Note: When dealing with text fields in PageMonster, It is important to
        remember to  press the return key.  Failure to select the return
        key will cause PageMonster to not add the text to the code window.


Once you have entered in all your text click on ADD. If you repeat this
operation again the resulting code in the @{"CODE WINDOW" link "notes" 27} will show two  blocks
of text separated by the HTML tag <P>. The <P> tag or paragraph tag is
interpreted by your web browser as a blank space that separates lines of
text or paragraphs.

 PageMonster also allows you to apply text styles to individual or multiple
lines of text and/or words.

 Note:  You can apply any of the text styles to individual words by
        isolating the word in its own text field. For example: suppose you
        wanted to  embed a hyperlink to the Amicrawler search engine in
        the following text line: 

      "Search for all Amiga related pages on the Net using Amicrawler"

You would have previously defined a STORED LINK in the MEDIA MODULE pointing
to:        

             http://www.amicrawler.com and assigned it to LINK 1.

 Then in the first text field of the PARAGRAPH MODULE you would type:

       "Search for all Amiga related pages on the Net using"

       Next in the Second text field you would type:  "Amicrawler"

 You would then select the LINE button, L2 to the left of the field in which
you typed  the word, "Amicrawler".  Finally select GET LINKS, then LINK 1
and then select ADD.   When you PREVIEW the resulting code, the text will
appear as a single line of text in your browser, but the word Amicrawler
will appear as a hyperlink. 

 To the left of each text field is a line button (L1 through L9).  You may
select all of the text lines by clicking on the ALL button or deselect all
of the text lines by clicking on the CLR button.  When the line buttons are
active, you may choose to apply the following styles:


 BREAK 
   
   Breaks a line of text.  Text will appear the exact same length in the
   web browser as it  does in the text field.  

 CENTER 

   Centers a line of text. Justification of text line will appear as
   centered in the web browser.

 BOLD

   Text line will appear as bolded text in the web browser.

 ITALIC

   Text line will appear as italicized text in the web browser.  

 UNDERLINED

   Text line will appear as underlined text in web
   browser. 

 GET LINKS

   Selecting GET LINKS will pop up a button menu that allows you to
   apply a predefined  hyperlink, previously created in the @{"STORED LINKS" link "Other" 195}
   MODULE.
  

   Other controls located at the bottom of the paragraph module are:


 MAIN MENU

   Selecting this button returns you to PageMonster's main menu.

 PREVIEW 

   Selecting this button will call up your @{"configured Web browser" link "Config" 35} and
   preview the HTML code currently written in the PARAGRAPH MODULE's code
   window.  

 RESET

   Gives you option to reset the code window, the text fields or both.

 LOAD ASCII

   Selecting this button will launch a pop up menu, from which you
   may select the following options:

   LOAD - Select LOAD import an ascii file (text only) as 
          "pre-formatted text" into the PARAGRAPH MODULE's @{"CODE WINDOW" link "notes" 27}.
          This means that text loaded using this function will appear in
          the web browser exactly as it was originally formatted. 

    Note: The best way to utilize the LOAD ASCII function is to create a
          number of separate ascii files using a text editor such as Ed.
          Ed can be run by opening a shell window and typing something
          like, "ed ram:mytext.txt". Load the files one after another 
          using APPEND under the LOAD ASCII function.  The files will 
          appear as separate paragraphs when viewed in your web browser. 

   EDIT - EDIT opens the configured text editor so you may edit text that
          is added to the PARAGRAPH MODULE's CODE WINDOW as pre-formatted 
          text.

 APPEND - APPEND allows an individual ascii text file as one paragraph.


 HELP

   Selecting HELP will load PageMonster's AmigaGuide on-line 
   documentation.


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "List" "The List Module"


                            THE LIST MODULE



 The list module is where you can organize information into different types
of lists.  This module is helpful when glossaries, bibliographys, outlines
and indexes are required in your Web pages. To utilize the list module you
must first select one of the four list generators.  A description of each
list generator is as follows:

 ORDERED LIST

   An Ordered list is a list that has items that are listed in numerical
   order. For example: 1. 2. 3. 4...etc.  Selecting ORDERED  in the 
   LIST MODULE's main screen, opens the ORDERED LIST GENERATOR.  
   From here you can enter  a list item in each of the separate fields
   provided.  List items can be either a word or a text string of up to
   100 characters in length. Once you have entered your list items you can
   then select any of the following options:

 CLEAR 

   Clears all of the text fields in the current screen.

 ACCEPT 

   Selecting ACCEPT informs PageMonster to begin building the list.  A
   selection requestor will appear and ask you if you would like to add
   additional items to the list.  Selecting YES will put you back in the
   ORDERED LIST window where you may then type in more items. This feature
   allows you to create lists of unlimited size.  If you select NO, the 
   code  will be written into the LIST MODULE's CODE WINDOW.  
   No must be selected when you have finished creating the list.

 CANCEL

   Cancels the ORDERED LIST operation.

 NEST LIST 

   This selection only appears after you have selected ADD ADDITIONAL
   ITEMS, and is useful when creating simple outlines.  When selected, 
   PageMonster writes what you have entered into the CODE WINDOW, but
   the HTML tag </ol> which signifies the end of an ordered list is not
   added.
   This allows you to begin building another list.  It is this list that
   becomes nested and indented from the first list.  To complete the
   nesting operation you must select ENDOF ORDERED in the LIST MODULE's
   main screen, for as many times that you have lists nested. 
    In other words, all of your lists must have a beginning and ending 
   tag in order for the code to be correct. 

   For example, to create the following list:

   I. This is the first item.
 
      Select YES to ADDITIONAL ITEMS then select NEST LIST.

          A.  This is the first item of the first nested list.  

          Select YES to ADDITIONAL ITEMS and then select NEST LIST again.

                          1. This is the first item of the second nested
                             list.


 Select ACCEPT when this list is completed.  To begin a new list at this
point you must first select the ENDOF ORDERED button twice to end the
nestting operation in the above list.


 ENDOF ORDERED

   This button is used when creating a nested list with the ORDERED LIST 
   generator. It inserts the HTML tag </ol> into the LIST MODULE's
   CODE WINDOW.  This tag signifies the end of an ORDERED LIST.  (See the
   explanation of the ORDERED LIST generator for details on how to use this
   feature).



 UNORDERED LIST

   The UNORDERED LIST generator operates exactly the same way
   that the ORDERED LIST generator does. The only difference is that an
   UNORDERED LIST places bullets at the beginning of each item instead of
   listing the items numerically.  If you select LOAD GRAPHIC in the LIST
   MODULE's main screen before beginning an UNORDERED LIST, the selected
   graphic will be placed at the  beginning of each listed item. 
   Please review the steps outlined in the ORDERED LIST section of this 
   manual to understand how an UNORDERED LIST is created.

 ENDOF UNORDERED

   This button is used when creating a nested list with the UNORDERED LIST 
   generator. It inserts the HTML tag </ul> into the LIST MODULE's CODE
   WINDOW.  This tag signifies the end of an UNORDERED LIST  (See the 
   explanation of the ORDERED LIST generator for details on how to use 
   this feature).

 DEFINITION LIST

   The DEFINITION LIST GENERATOR creates a list formatted like a glossary
   or dictionary.  Selecting DEFINITION in the LIST MODULE's
   main screen opens the definition list generator. First type in a
   DEFINITION TITLE. This is the word or text string you would like to
   define.
   Next type in a definition using the text fields in the window labeled 
   DEFINITION. When completed you may select either of the following:

 ACCEPT 

   Selecting this option informs PageMonster to begin building the
   definition list.  A selection requestor will appear.  If you wish to add
   additional items, select  YES.  Selecting YES will put you back in the
   DEFINITION LIST GENERATOR where you can enter the next definition.  
   This feature allows you to create a list of definitions of 
   unlimited size. If you select NO, the code will be written into the
   LIST MODULE's CODE WINDOW.

        NO, must be selected when you have finished creating the list. 
        If you select LOAD GRAPHIC in the LIST MODULE's main screen before
        building a DEFINITION LIST, the selected graphic will be placed
        at the beginning of each listed item.  

 CANCEL 

   Cancels the definition list operation.



 LINKED LIST 

   The LINKED LIST generator creates a list of links. which can be linked 
   to a predefined hyperlink that you must have previously set in the 
   @{"STORED LINKS MODULE" link "Other" 195}, located in the MEDIA MODULE.  The list generator
   is probably the most helpful when you want to create a text index to a
   number of media files such as pictures, song modules, sound samples and
   animations.  To create a LINKED LIST select LINKED in the 
   LIST GENERATOR's main screen. When the LINKED LIST generator opens, 
   type in a LIST TITLE.

   Note: The LIST TITLE may only be typed in once for the current list.

   Next type the list Items into each of their respective fields.  You will
   notice that to the right of each field there is a button labeled LINK.
   Selecting this button will allow you to access the STORED LINKS panel.
   After selecting the appropriate link you should see the HTML code
   referencing your list item in the text field.  

   When you have completed creating your list and linking all of the text 
   fields, you can now select either of the following:

 CLEAR

   Clears all of the text fields.

 ACCEPT

   Selecting this option informs PageMonster to build the linked
   list and write its code into the LIST MODULE's CODE WINDOW.  
   In this version of PageMonster, a LINKED LIST is limited to 10 
   entries per list. However, you can create multiple LINKED LISTs,
   each with its own LIST TITLE. 

 CANCEL

   Cancels the LINKED LIST GENERATOR's operation.

 LOAD GRAPHIC

   Selecting this button launches a file requestor asking for a
   bullet graphic to load.  From here you can select a graphic file 
   and then select OK.  When the file type requestor appears, select 
   the file extension that is appropriate for the file that you have 
   selected.  If the file already has an extension select NONE. 
   You will know that this feature is active by the red outline of this 
   button.  

 PREVIEW

   Selecting this button will preview the HTML  code in the LIST MODULE's 
   CODE WINDOW in the configured browser.  

 RESET

   Resets the LIST MODULE's CODE WINDOW.  All code in the CODE WINDOW
   will be lost.

 MAIN MENU

   Selecting this button will return you to  PageMonster's MAIN MENU.


 @{"Return to the Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Forms" "The Forms Module"
     

                          
                               THE FORMS MODULE



 A form's purpose in a Web page is to retrieve feedback from people who are
interested in what you have to offer on your Web site.  A form can be used
to request all types of information.  You can build order forms, product
catalogs, questionnaires, or just simply ask for a persons name and Email
address.  When a person fills out a form on your Web page and submits it,
the information is sent back to your Email address.  This process is
controlled by a program or a script that sits on your service provider's
computer. This script is commonly referred to as the CGI SCRIPT.  

 PageMonster makes the task of implementing all of the above mentioned
processes extremely simple.  All you have to do is select the appropriate
forms generator, fill in your information, click a few buttons and the HTML
code is created for you.  If you have correctly entered the necessary
information in the @{"FORM ACTION" link "Config" 102} field located in the @{"CONFIGURATION MODULE" link "Config" 0},
you will be able to create working forms quickly without any hassles.

 Currently, the FORMS MODULE supports four different types of forms. 
 They are as follows:

 THE ADDRESS FORM GENERATOR

   Click on ADDRESS FORM to open the ADDRESS FORM generator's screen. 
   Type in a FORM TITLE.  This text will appear at the top of the form.
   Select one of the four options available. 

   They are:

        1. Ask for Name and Email Address 

        2. Ask for Name Email Address and Feedback

        3. Ask for Name Street Address and Email Address 

        4. Ask for Name Street Address  Email and Feedback

   If you select either option 2 or option 4 you can specify FEEDBACK
   TITLE this text will appear above the text field area when the form
   is displayed in the browser.  Finally select ACCEPT and the forms
   HTML code will be written into the form generator's CODE WINDOW.
   Selecting CANCEL will cancel the address form operation.

 THE CATALOG FORM GENERATOR

   Click on CATALOG FORM to open the CATALOG FORM generator's screen.
   Type in the ITEM NAME of the first catalog item. Next enter an ITEM 
   NUMBER.  This is the catalog reference number.  Finally enter the ITEM
   price  and ITEM DESCRIPTION. These entries should be self explanatory.
   You may now select any of the following options: 

   USE IMAGE

     Selecting this button will launch a file requestor asking you to
     select an inline image. This could be a company logo or a picture of
     the catalog item you are entering. Select an image and then click on 
     OK.  Next you will be asked to select a file extension.  
     If the image file you selected already has an extension, select NONE.
     At this point another pop up menu will appear and ask you if you would
     like to link the image to an external file. If you select NO you will
     be returned to the CATALOG GENERATOR's screen. If you select YES 
     another file requestor will appear asking you to select an external
     file. After selecting the file you will  again be asked to select a 
     file extension. If you select NONE a menu will appear.
     You must select the correct DIRECTORY, depending on the type of
     file you  selected, either PICS or SOUNDS.

  
   NEXT ITEM

     Selecting this button adds the current product to the form.
     You may now enter in information for the next item.  You must select
     NEXT ITEM before you can add a new item or before you can select
     ACCEPT.

   PAYMENT OPTIONS

     Activating this switch will add some generic payment
     options.  This module creates three radio buttons that are labeled
     VISA, MASTERCARD and UPS. It also creates a field labeled credit 
     card #.  The labels for these fields can be edited by clicking on
     the FORM's CODE WINDOW.  You may manually edit them in the configured
     text editor.  If your text editor has a find and replace feature,
     you can quickly change the labels in this manner.

   ACCEPT

     Selecting accept will build the form and write it's code into the
     FORM MODULE's CODE WINDOW.  NEXT ITEM must be selected first.  
            

   CANCEL

     Selecting this button will cancel the CATALOG generator operation.



 THE ORDER FORM GENERATOR

   Click on ORDER FORM to open the ORDER FORM GENERATOR screen. 
   Type in an ITEM NAME.  This is the name of the product that you are
   adding to the form.
   Next type in some ITEM VARIATIONS. These fields are used to add 
   product variations.  

   For example: 

   If the product is a T-shirt, the variations may be
   small, medium and large.  Or , blue,gold and red for colors.
   Once you have entered in all your information YOU MUST then select 
   ADD TO LIST and then NEXT ITEM, before you can enter in a new item or 
   build the form.

   You also have the following options:

   USE SELECTION LIST 

     Turning this switch ON will put the ITEM  variations
     into a selection list when the form is built. 

   USE CHECK BOXES

     Turning this switch ON will assign check boxes to each ITEM
     VARIATION when the form is built.

  USE RADIO BUTTONS

     Turning this switch ON will assign radio  buttons to each
     ITEM VARIATION when the form is built.

  PAYMENT OPTIONS

     Activating this switch will add some generic Payment
     options into the form. This option creates three radio buttons 
     that are labeled Visa, MASTERCARD and UPS. It also creates a field
     labeled credit card #.  The labels for these fields can be modified
     by clicking on the FORM's CODE WINDOW, where you may manually
     alter them in your configured text editor.  
     If your text editor has a find and replace feature it may be
     wise to change the labels in this manner.

  ACCEPT

     Builds the order form. All items that are to appear in the current
     form must be added before selecting accept.

  CANCEL

     Cancels the ORDER FORM operation. 


 QUESTIONNAIRE FORM GENERATOR

   The QUESTIONNAIRE FORM GENERATOR is used to create things such as
   surveys, simple multipule selection tests or anything that requires you
   to ask a series of questions. To open the QUESTIONNAIRE FORM generator's
   screen Click on QUESTIONNAIRE. 

   First type in the FORM TITLE. This is the heading that will appear
  at the top of the QUESTIONNAIRE FORM you are currently working on.

   note: once NEXT QUESTION is selected you cannot change the FORM TITLE.

   Next Type in a QUESTION. This is the current question you are asking.
   Now type in some ANSWERS for the question. These fields will appear
   as  multiple selections in the form.  Once all the information for the
   current question is entered you may select NEXT QUESTION.
   At this point you may either add a new question by repeating the above
   steps or build the form by selecting ACCEPT.  Before you build the form,
   you can select from the following  options:

   ADD SURVEY INFORMATION

     If this switch is turned ON, questions regarding a person's gender,
     age group and income bracket will be added to the beginning
     of the questionnaire. USE CHECK BOXES Turning this switch ON will
     assign check boxes to each ANSWER when the form is built.

   USE RADIO BUTTONS

     Turning this switch ON will assign radio buttons to each
     ANSWER when the form is built.

  CANCEL

     Cancels the QUESTIONNAIRE FORM'S operation.

 SB (SEARCH BUTTON)
   
   Selecting SB which stands for search button will pop up
   a requestor asking you what type of button you want to create.
   You may select either:

   SEARCH TERM

     Selecting this button prompts you to type in a search term.
     Entering the term and then pressing RETURN will cause PageMonster
     to write the code for this button into the FORMS MODULES code window.
     When the code is previewed in the browser the label of the button will
     reflect what you typed in the field.
     If you are on-line and click on this button the search term will be 
     submitted to the Alta Vista search engine. 
     You MUST type a + symbol between words if you have more then one word
     in your search term otherwise Alta Vista will only recognize the
     first word of the search term that you typed. 

     For example:

     High Schools in the USA should be entered in as:
     High+Schools+in+the+USA.   

   CREATE CUSTOM

     Selecting this button prompts you to TYPE IN A URL FOR THE
     BUTTON you want to create.  This can point to a web page address,
     a query to another search engine or a file. (SEE FOOTNOTE)  Next 
     TYPE IN A BUTTON LABEL. This is the text that will appear on the
     button when the form is viewed in the browser. You now have the 
     option of selecting what METHOD the button should use to send the
     data.

     GET - Will append a question mark at the end of the URL. This method 
           should only be used if you are well versed in HTML and have some
           special use for it.  It is highly suggested that the POST method
           is used.

    POST - Is the default when the CREATE CUSTOM menu opens. You will
           probably have more successful results if you just leave this
           option alone, unless you know what you are doing need to 
           change it.


  

 OTHER AREAS OF CONTROL IN THE FORMS MODULES MAIN SCREEN 


 MAIN MENU

   Selecting this button will return you to PageMonster's main
   menu.

 PREVIEW

   Previews the code currently written in the form module's CODE
   WINDOW with the configured web browser. 

 PLUG-IN

   This function is also available in the main menu and can be used to
   add more HTML generators to the form module.  Selecting this button
   launches a pop-up menu that asks you  what type of plug-in you would
   like to use. This can be a AVF file (AmigaVision application), an 
   executable or an arexx script. 
   @{"(SEE GETTING PLUG-INS AND CREATING YOUR OWN PLUG-INS)" link "Plug-in" 0}  

 RESET

   Resets the form module's CODE WINDOW.  All previously written code
   will be lost.

 FOOTNOTE A: 

   URL stands for Universal Resource Locator.  The URL tells your
   web browser where to find a web page, a file or where to send 
   information to be acted upon by a CGI script.

     Some examples of URLS:

     http://www.yahoo.com - is the location of the yahoo search engines
     main web page.

     http://atozweb.com/pages/pics/logo.jpg - is the location on the 
     Internet of the picture file logo.jpg

     sounds/cool.mod - is the location of the song module cool being 
     referenced from the current directory.

     http://altavista.digital.com/cgi bin/query?pg=q&what=web&fmt=&q=soccer
     - points the search term "soccer" to the cgi script "query" located
     on the alta vista server.
@endnode

@node "Index" "The Index Module"


                             THE INDEX MENU




  The INDEX MENU is used to create a main index for pages that have 
  already been built and saved by the Pagemonster. This feature is what 
  allows you to create web sites with many web pages that are interlinked.
  This feature should only be used during the final stages of building
  a large web site. 

  The easiest way to utilize the Index menu is to do the following:  
  First while in EDIT MODE open the Index menu by clicking on INDEX in
  Pagemonsters MAIN MENU. In the top left portion of the INDEX MENU'S 
  window you will notice five text fields. 
  Type in the titles of the pages that you are linking to.

  For example: Introduction, Download Page, Favorite links etc...

  To the right of each field is a button switch. Set the switch next to
  the first field to ON by selecting it. Next select LINK DIRECTORY. 
  A directory requestor will appear asking you to select a Pagemonster 
  Project directory.
  If you had previously created a project named Introduction you
  would now select the project directory of the same name. 
  PageMonster will then copy the directory and all its relevant files
  and directories into the current project. You should now see a link
  that looks something like this in the first field:


     <A HREF="Introduction/Introduction.html">Introduction</A>

  This HTML code links the file Introduction.html that sits in the 
  current project directory called Introduction to the Index entry 
  named Introduction.
  Repeat these steps for each index entry you want to link a page to and
  then select ACCEPT. Another requestor will appear asking you if you want 
  to APPEND or CONTINUE. If you select APPEND you will be returned to
  the index menu where you may add more entries. This allows you to create
  indexes of unlimited size, so you are not just limited to five fields
  per index.

  When you are finished creating your index select CONTINUE. 
  You can now access the indexes code by changing to ASSEMBLY MODE in 
  Pagemonster's MAIN MENU and the selecting INDEX.



  In addition the Index menu also supports the following options.

  BULLETS - selecting this button will launch a file requestor
            asking you to select a graphic bullet. You can select
            one of the Pagemonster defaults or one of your own.
            Once a bullet is selected, a pop up requestor will appear
            asking if you would like to add a file extension.
            If your graphic already has a extension select NONE.
            This option must be used before you begin building your Index
            or before selecting ACCEPT.


    FILES - selecting this button will launch a file requestor
            asking you to select a file to copy. You can select any
            type of file to link to. For example :

            If you had a web page named example.html that was not created
            by Pagemonster, you could add it to the current directory by 
            selecting it in the FILES requestor. Any graphic files linked 
            to the page such as pic1.gif, Pic2.gif etc..could also be added
            just by selecting them in the FILES requestor. You can now
            create a index link for example.html by replacing the text 
            "http://" which is the default in the ADD FIELD, with the text 
            "example.html". Set the switch to the right of the first entry
            field to  ON and type "See Example" in the field. 
            Finally select the ADD button. If successful the code generated
            in the first entry field will look something like:

                       <A HREF="example.html">See Example</A>

    RESET - Selecting this button will clear any entry fields that have
            been set to ON. This is the only working button outside of
            INDEX MENU'S window as indicated by the RESET button
            being outlined in blue.


 CENTERED - Setting this switch to ON will center the Index in the page
            when it is displayed in the web browser. 


   TABLES - Setting this switch to ON will build the Index using tables.

   CANCEL - Cancels the INDEX MENU's operation.


    

                

             

             

    

@endnode

@node "Tutorial" "The PageMonster Tutorial"
                             

                                TUTORIAL


We will assume that you have successfully @{"installed PageMonster" link "Install" 0}, and that
you are about to enter PageMonster.  We also assume that you are somewhat
familiar with the Amiga Operating system.  If you are a new Amiga user, you
should become familiar with the operating system, file structure,  file
naming, and last but not lease, true multi-tasking.

 Okay, let's create a quick Web page.  Follow the step by step tutorial
below to get a quick understanding of PageMonster's interface.

 Step 1 

   From your Workbench double click the left mouse button on the
   PageMonster 1.0 icon to open the program.

 Step 2

   The @{"CONFIGURATION SCREEN" link "Config" 0} will appear after the title animation.
   Enter the paths to your various programs.  (ie...dh0:DpaintV/Dpaint®)
   Enter the Web addresses that pertain to the project you want to 
   edit or create.  In some cases, an additional option must be entered
   after the path so your program will start with PageMonster's file 
   loaded, rather than no file at all. 

   See your program's user manual for the correct option.  

   For DeluxePaint V® that option is -f.  
   
   Save your settings and start PageMonster.

 Step 3

   In the @{"MAIN MENU" link "MMenu" 0} select @{"SET BACKGROUND." link "Background" 0}  Then, under BG BUFFERS
   select IMAGE 1.  Next click on the button labeled ROYAL BLUE and select
   TEXT. Then click on the button labeled TURQUOISE and select LINK, 
   Finally click on the button labeled AQUAMARINE, select VLINK then 
   select ACCEPT.

 Step 4 

   In the MAIN MENU select TITLE. The @{"TITLE MODULE" link "Title" 0} will appear.  At
   the TEXT ENTRY LINE type "The Dinosaur Homepage" , then click on ADD.
   The title code should appear in the CODE WINDOW.  

   Finally select MAIN MENU to return to the MAIN MENU.

 Step 5

   Back in the MAIN MENU you may select @{"RESET" link "MMenu" 74} and in the pop up panel
   select CONTINUE.  The title and background tags should now appear in
   the MAIN MENU'S CODE WINDOW, written in the proper HTML format.

 Step 6 

   In the MAIN MENU select HEADER.  The @{"HEADER MODULE" link "header" 0} will appear.  At
   the TEXT ENTRY LINE type "The Dinosaur Information page". Press return 
   then  select HEADER 1,  select CENTER and click on ADD.  Next, in the 
   TEXT ENTRY  LINE type "The Stegosaurus".  Press return then select 
   HEADER 2, select CENTER and click on ADD. The header code should now
   appear in the CODE WINDOW.  
   
   You should then select MAIN MENU to return to main.

 Step 7

   In the MAIN MENU select MEDIA LINKS.  In the @{"MEDIA MODULE" link "Media" 0}, Under
   SELECT A LOAD FUNCTION, choose INLINE IMAGE. When the file requestor
   appears go to the directory PAGEMONSTER:demo/ and select the file named,
   "dino.gif".  Select ok and a pop up panel should appear.  Next click on
    NONE since the filename already has a file extension attached. 

    Note:  The construction of Web pages is dependent upon many different
           file types.  How they are named and case sensitivity are very
           important issues.
           
           It is absolutely crucial that all files are properly named. 
           Since so many personal computers on the net use the so called
           "eight dot three" convention of file naming, your Web page
           construction should conform to the least intelligent operating
           system.  This allows your pages to be accessed by anyone 
           browsing your home page.

    Now, select EXTERNAL FILE, go to the directory PAGEMONSTER:demo/ again
    and select the file named, " dino.wav".  Then, select NONE in the
    pop up panel since the file extension is already attached.
    
    Finally, select CENTER then ADD. The code should now appear in the 
    CODE WINDOW. 

    Return to the MAIN MENU by clicking on MAIN MENU.

 Step 8

    In the MAIN MENU select PARAGRAPH.  In the @{"PARAGRAPH MODULE" link "paragraph" 0}  choose
    LOAD ASCII.  When the file requestor opens go to the directory
    PAGEMONSTER:demo/ and select the file named, "dino.txt".  

    The code should now appear in the CODE WINDOW.   
    
    Return to Main by clicking on MAIN MENU.

 Step 9

    Now let's assemble the main code.  Select the button labeled 
    EDIT MODE In the MAIN MENU . This will switch PageMonster into 
    ASSEMBLE MODE.

    Next click on MEDIA LINK.  You should now see the media modules 
    code written in the CODE WINDOW.
  
    Repeat this step, except select the buttons labeled HEADER, and then
    PARAGRAPH.  You should now see all of the code written into the main
    display screen.

 Step 10 

    If you configured your web browser in the @{"CONFIGURATION MODULE" link "Config" 0} 
    (step 1) you can select PREVIEW in the MAIN MENU.
  
    You should now be viewing a basic Web page.  Test out the link by
    clicking on the dino picture. This will only work, if you have 
    your browser configured to play .wav samples. 

    You will automatically return to PageMonster when you quit the
    browser  program.

 If you followed the above steps correctly you should now have an
 understanding of the logic behind PageMonster's interface.  

 To further demonstrate this go into ASSEMBLE MODE and select LOAD.
 The Page Design template panel should appear.  
 Select any of the design styles. After the code is reassembled select
 PREVIEW.  Try this a number of times using different design templates.

 As you can see PageMonster's modular page generation is very powerful. 
 There are many more features within PageMonster but, this exercise is 
 meant to be a quick peek.  PageMonster was designed to be user friendly
 and intuitive.  Please explore the program.  If you have the Amiga 
 translator library and narrator device installed, your system or if
 you have installed the @{"digitized voice samples" link "Config" 124}, you may use the @{"SPEECH" link "Config" 120} 
 option.   

 Activate the @{"SPEECH" link "Config" 120} option in the CONFIGURATION MODULE.  
 This feature is meant to coach you through the program until you're 
 ready to go solo.


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Plug-in" "Making Your own Plug-ins"
 


                             THE PLUG-IN MENU  



  The Plug-in menu was created for the purpose of expanding PageMonsters
 capabilities. The basic idea would be to create plug-ins that could
 focus upon specific task related to the WWW and web page building.
 For instance, The table Plug-in included in the Pagemonster
 distribution, is designed to build tables utilizing all of Pagemonster's 
 other HTML code modules.  

  Other included plug-ins, can communicate with
 the Amiga OS and other external programs. This is the case with the
 arexx script named paint.rexx. This arexx script can recall a variable 
 containing the name of the last inline image that was loaded
 and then pass it on to the paint program that you  specified in the 
 @{"CONFIGURATION MODULE" link "Config" 0}.

  Once the image has been modified and saved back to ram:html/pics/
 the script will then preview the results in the configured 
 web browser and write html code that can then be accessed from
 the Pagemonster.

  So a plug-in can be almost anything, an Amigados script, a Arexx script, 
 a AmigaVision application or even an executable program. It can create
 a specific type of web page, use previously created HTML code and
 interact with external programs.   
 


                         CREATING YOUR OWN PLUG-INS

                    (For Intermediate to Advanced Users)



     
  To get a basic understanding of how a Plug-in can work with the 
  pagemonster we will look at three different methods:


  1. AMIGADOS SCRIPTS


  Although this is probably the most limiting method you can use. 
  There are still a few operations that you can create using Amigados
  scripts. Don't forget to set the script protection bit using the
  Amigados command PROTECT so that your script can be loaded from
  the executable requestor in the @{"PLUG-IN MENU" link "Main" 0}.

                          From the shell type: 

                   protect pagemonster:myscript.scpt +s 

  To get an idea of how the Pagemonster can utilize an Amigados script
  study the script supplied bellow called Onlineb.scpt 

  This script is an amigados script that allows you to go on-line 
  from inside the Pagemonster and connect to the Pagemonster support page
  on our web server.

  This script assumes that the following files exist in the pagemonster
  directory and that they contain the correct paths of where 
  the applications exist in your system. So if you are using TermiteTCP
  and it is located in work:TTCP/ , then the first line of the file 
  named TermiteTCPPath should read work:TTCP/TermiteTCP. 

  The script is designed to copy this file into ENV: where it can the be
  used as the environment variable $TermiteTCPPath during the scripts
  execution.



;                            Onlineb.scpt



; Allows you to access Pagemonster's Support Page.

; (The first part of the script checks to see if the required files ;
containing the desired application paths exist in the Pagemonster ;
directory.)


If exists Pagemonster:MiamiPath
 copy Pagemonster:MiamiPath TO env:  endif

If exists Pagemonster:TermiteTCPPath
 copy Pagemonster:TermiteTCPPath TO env:  endif

If exists Pagemonster:AmiTCPPath
 copy Pagemonster:AmiTCPPath TO env: endif

If exists Pagemonster:Browser
 copy Pagemonster:Browser TO env:  endif

If exists Pagemonster:support_page
 copy Pagemonster:support_page TO env:  endif

; (The next part of the script uses the Amiga OS3.0+ command ;requestchoice
to create a workbench menu to start up your  ;TCP stack from.)


REQUESTCHOICE >ENV:RECNUM "SELECT A TCP STACK" "Connect to Support  Page?"
"TermiteTCP" "Miami" "AmiTCP" "NO!"

; (note:The above 2 lines should all be on one line)

IF $RECNUM EQ "3"  execute $AmiTCPPath  Endif

IF $RECNUM EQ "2"  run $MiamiPath  Endif  

IF $RECNUM EQ "1"  run $TermiteTCPPath  Endif
  

IF $RECNUM EQ "0"  echo ""  echo "    OPERATION CANCELED "   echo ""  Endif

; (The final part of the script uses requestchoice again to create ;another
workbench menu to load the web browser and open the URL   ;pointing to the
Pagemonster Support Page on the Internet)



REQUESTCHOICE >ENV:RECNUM "Waiting...." "Load $Browser?" "OK" "CANCEL" 

IF $RECNUM EQ "0"  echo ""  echo "    Returning to Pagemonster "  echo ""
Endif

IF $RECNUM EQ "1"  $Browser $support_Page  Endif

echo "    Returning to Pagemonster " 


 Although using Amigados allows you to do some simple operations and
 you can call the append command to assemble existing scripts,
 A much better way to design your plug-in would be to use Arexx.




 2.AREXX SCRIPTS

 
 The following example is a simplified version of whats possible. 
 It does not use any of the paint programs internal functions but if your
 paint program does have an arexx command set you can modify the 
 script bellow using  these commands to control the programs internal 
 functions. Just make sure that the program you are using the script for
 is specified in the CONFIGURATION MODULE.



/* PAINT.REXX SCRIPT */


/* First call the variables from Pagemonster into Arexx */

address AV.REXX 

OPTIONS RESULTS

GETVAR ldrexx1 

newfile=RESULT

GETVAR ppicname 

name=RESULT

GETVAR PLAYER5 

prog=RESULT

/* 
 * The next line loads the the last selected inline image 
 * into the configured paint program. 
 */

address command prog newfile

/* 
 * After saving to ram:html/pics and quiting the above paint program
 * the following lines of the script will create HTML code referencing 
 * the inline image.   
 */

taga = '<CENTER><IMG SRC="pics/'

tagb = '"></CENTER>'

pin1 = insert(taga , name)   pin2 = insert(pin1 , tagb)

CALL OPEN test, 'ram:html/Image2.html' , write   CALL WRITELN test, pin2
CLOSE test

/* 
 * The next command  copies the file created above over the existing
 * code for the MEDIA MODULE so that it can be accessed by the  
 * Pagemonster. The append command can be sustituted for copy. 
 */

address command 'copy ram:html/Image2.html to ram:html/Image.html'

/* The next command loads the finished code into AWEB-II to 
 * preview for 30 seconds before returning to Pagemonster.
 */



address command 'run AWEB-II:AWEB-II file://localhost/ram:html/Image.html'

address command 'wait 30'



 3. AMIGAVISION APPLICATION


 It's assumed that you have an understanding of how to use AmigaVision
 to utilize the following information. 

 The plug-in module loads a AmigaVision application through an execute
 Icon that is set to accept arexx scripts in the execute icon's call mode.

 What this means is that any AmigaVision application loaded from this
 menu will inherit all of PageMonsters global variables listed in TABLE A.

 Do not declare these variables at the beginning of your application
 since they were created when Pagemonster was started and already exist.

 You will have to test your application from inside the Pagemonster
 so that it can find these variables.

 After  your application runs it should write any resulting code
 to any of Pagemonster's HTML modules listed in TABLE B.

 You can do this by using the Output Icon under the Data menu 
 and setting it to one of the paths listed in TABLE B. make sure
 that you have a dummy file of the same name setup in ram:html
 so you can load it in the Output modules file requestor when the
 Output Icon is set to output to a file name.  



                                TABLE A



                  
                          PAGEMONSTER VARIABLES



              LOCATION = The default URL or web page address

               BROWSER = The current selected web browser

                EDITOR = The current selected text editor

               VIEWER1 = The current selected graphics viewer

               PLAYER1 = The current selected sample player

               PLAYER4 = The current selected song module player

               PLAYER5 = The current selected paint program 
                         or image proccesor

              BROWSER3 = The current default directory

                LOCALD = The current selected storage directory

                  PORT = The default form action HTML tag

               OPTIONS = The default domain name
  
               EDITOR4 = The default email address

              ppicname = The last inline image loaded



                                 TABLE B
                        


                   HTML MODULES AND REQUIRED SAVE PATHS



                    Title Module = ram:html/title.html

                   Header Module = ram:html/header.html 

                    Media Module = ram:html/image.html

                Paragraph Module = ram:html/para.html

                     List Module = ram:html/list.html

                     Form Module = ram:html/forms.html

                    Index Module = ram:html/index.html

                   plug-in Module = ram:html/plugin.html


 @{"Return to the Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Export" "The Export Project Module"



                        THE EXPORT PROJECT MODULE



 The export project module can be used to save, compress or upload
 completed Pagemonster projects. 

 To utilize the export project module in the simplest manner do the 
 following:

 Open the export project module by selecting SAVE in PageMonsters 
 MAIN MENU. Then, type in a PROJECT NAME. It is probably wise to use 
 only one word for this entry. 


 Next, select PROJECT DIRECTORY. This will launch a directory requestor 
 asking you to select a directory to save your project to. 
 You may also use the device buttons DEF, SYS:, DF0: or RAM:. 

    Note: selecting DEF will use the @{"default storage directory" link "Config" 89} path 
          that you had previously configured in the CONFIGURATION MODULE.


 Finally select ACCEPT. Using the PROJECT NAME, Pagemonster
 will create a directory inside of the PROJECT DIRECTORY that you have 
 just selected. The entire contents of the current project will then be 
 copied here and can be loaded back into the program by selecting the LOAD 
 button in PageMonsters MAIN MENU.

 
 In addition the Export project module also supports the following
 options:



 COMPRESS DIRECTORY 

   Selecting this button will execute the ARCHIVE COMMAND written in
   the corresponding field. The default is 

              "lha a -r hompage.lha ram:html/#?" 

   If you have LHA installed in  your c: directory, the entire contents 
   of the current project directory will be compressed into an LHA file 
   and then saved to the directory that is specified in the 
   PROJECT DIRECTORY FIELD. Clicking on the outer outline of the 
   compress directory button will cycle through the default commands 
   allowing support for other archive formats such as ZIP. 
   But again, you must also have these commands installed in the c: 
   directory for this to work. 
    


 GO ONLINE 

   Selecting this button will execute an Amigados script that prompts you
   to select one of the following TCP stacks:

                        TermiteTCP  Miami  AmiTCP

   This will allow you to dialup your internet provider so that you can 
   test your  web pages online. This comes in handy especially when you 
   want to  upload a page or test links to pages located elsewhere on the
   Internet.  


 UPLOAD 

   You may only use this function if you are Online using AmiTCP
   and  have Mountftp installed on your system. If You are using Miami or
   TermiteTCP see the AREXX SCRIPT operations outlined below.

   MountFtp requires that a directory with the icon's tool types reflecting
   your USERNAME and PASSWORD is setup in MountFtp/Hosts/.
   This icon should be named exactly the same name that you have typed 
   into in the DOMAIN NAME field. 

   When you select the UPLOAD button, Pagemonster sends a command to 
   the mountftp device, Ftp: which changes the directory to the remote
   directory specified in the DOMAIN NAME field. 

   If you need to add additional directories to the path, you can set the
   REMOTE DIRECTORY switch to active and then type them into the 
   corresponding field. 

   For example:

   If my providers domain name is www.aa.net and I need to upload to
   a directory named public_html. I would type /public_html in the
   REMOTE DIRECTORY FIELD. 

   After connecting and finding the desired directory Pagemonster will
   begin to prompt you with file requestors, asking you to select
   all the media files associated with the project. 

   Once you have finished selecting all the files needed from the 
   any of the file requestors SELECT CANCEL, and Pagemonster will
   prompt you with the next requestor. This operation can take some 
   time, especially if you are using large media files in your project.
  
   
 USING AREXX COMMANDS

   If you are using TermiteTCP or Miami or any other TCP stack then you
   will need to use a AREXX SCRIPT to control your favorite Ftp client. 

   To load an Arexx script select LOAD AREXX SCRIPT and then select the
   name of the script you want to load in the file requestor.
   If you are Online you can then run the script by selecting 
   RUN AREXX SCRIPT.

   Note: At the time of this release we are still working on a usable
         AREXX script for any of the Amiga FTP clients, Future support
         for this area will be found on the Pagemonster's on-line
         support page.     
      


 @{"Return to the Main Menu" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Other" "Media Module Sub Menus"



                       THE MEDIA MODULE SUB MENUS



                         THE RECORD SAMPLE MENU


 The record sample menu is accessed by selecting RECORD SAMPLE in the 
 MEDIA MODULES main menu. From this menu you can load a program or an 
 arexx script by selecting the LD button. You then have the option to
 run a your selection as a command or an arexx script by selecting the
 appropriate  toggle switch. 

 Make sure that the resulting file will end up being saved as
 "ram:html/sounds/generic.8svx" so that Pagemonster can create 
 the HTML code for it.

 You may also use the default command which calls a program named 
 AGMSRecordsound. This is a shell based sound sampling program that can
 be found on Aminet.

 To use the default command you must have AGMSRecordSound installed in c:
 and the correct sampling hardware to use with it.

 Selecting CANCEL will cancel the operation. 

 




                            THE AREXX MODULE


 The Arexx module is designed to simplify the process of passing a media
 file  from the Pagemonster to an external program using Arexx.

 This feature of Pagemonster was designed to make arexx interfacing easy
 for those users who have no knowledge of the Arexx programing language.
 If you are an advanced Arexx programer you may find the PLUG-IN feature
 located in the MAIN MENU, more useful to your needs.

 Using the Arexx module is easy as you will learn if you do the following:
 First select FILE TO PROCESS. Select the media file you would like to 
 process in the file requestor.

 Next, select APPLICATION TO USE. This is the application program that you
 want to pass the media file to. Select its file name in the file
 requestor.

 Now, select AREXX SCRIPT. This is one of the special default scripts
 that is located in the Pagemonster:scripts/rexxscripts directory.
 These scripts use special LOADREXXFILE and SAVEREXXFILE variables.

 (SEE: AREXX MODULE SCRIPTS.)
 
 Select the script that is appropriate for the application that you are 
 using.


 Finally select PROCESS. This will run the selected application and
 then the selected Arexx script using the specified file. This will take
 a moment, so be patient. Once the script is through processing, a number 
 of pop up requestors will appear asking you to select a file extension,
 a directory and if you want the code written as either an Inline Image or 
 an external file. 
 You will then be returned to the Media modules main screen where
 you may ADD the resulting code to the media modules code window.

 The Arexx module can also store and retrieve the settings that you load
 into its fields. You can do this by selecting INSERT NEW after loading
 a file, an application and a script. If you want to save a modified
 setting select SAVE SETUP. If you want to delete a setting, select
 DELETE. You can recall settings by  cycling through them with the
 NEXT button. 

 Finally you can rebuild the arexx script with the current
 settings by selecting MAKE SCRIPT. If for any reason you need to 
 edit the script or just want to view it you can load it into your
 configured text editor by clicking on the AREXX MODULE'S CODE WINDOW.

 Selecting RESET will clear the contents of this window.
 If you want to cancel the AREXX MODULES operation select CANCEL.



                         THE REMOTE LINKS MODULE


 This module is used to create links to other destinations on the internet.
 To use, just type in the web address you want to link to and then select
 ACCEPT. The resulting code is always written as an external file link.


 Other options on this menu are:


 DEFAULT 

   Inserts the default Web page address that was configured in the 
   CONFIGURATION MODULE into the URL field. 


 MAILTO 

   Creates a mailto: link using the email address that was configured in
   the CONFIGURATION MODULE. 


 HTTP:// 

   Inserts this text into the URL field (http server).


 FTP://

   Inserts this text into the URL field (ftp server).


 AMINET DIRECTORY 
 
   Aids in creating links to files located on Aminet. You must complete 
   the path to the archive.
 

 SIMTEL 

   Aids in creating links to the Simtel PC archives. You must complete 
   the path to the archive.
   

 OCTAMED PC PLAYER

   Creates a link to the Octamed PC Player page useful if you are using
   song modules on your site.



        
                           THE COMMAND BUTTON


  The COMMAND button can be a very powerful feature if you are using
  AWEB. This button supports the special aweb tag. 

                  <A HREF="x-aweb:command/<COMMAND>">

  This tag can be used to run local system commands but, it only 
  works when loading local files in AWEB. 

  To use this feature you may either select the top part of the word
  COMMAND which will open a string requestor where you can enter a 
  cli command. If you select the bottom part of the word command,
  you can select the command using a file requestor.

  Selecting the button outside of the word COMMAND activates the function.
  When the COMMAND button is activated the x-aweb tag will be added
  using the command you specified when you load an INLINED IMAGE.


                           THE VIEW/PLAY MENU


 The VIEW/PLAY menu is used to preview the media files before adding
 their HTML code to the media modules code window. This feature should
 be used only after an INLINE IMAGE or EXTERNAL FILE has already
 been loaded. Selecting INLINE will insert the path of the last 
 INLINE IMAGE selected. Selecting EXTERNAL will insert the path of
 the last EXTERNAL file selected. Selecting VIEWER, PLAYER or 
 MOD PLAYER will insert the paths of their corresponding defaults in
 the CONFIGURATION MODULE. Choosing ACCEPT causes Pagemonster to attempt
 to load the current file into the current viewer/player. CANCEL aborts
 the operation.




                                RESET BUTTON


 Selecting RESET will launch a pop up menu giving you the option to reset
 the DISPLAY the FIELD or ALL. If the DELETE FILES switch is active.

 Another menu will appear asking which directory in the current project
 would you like to delete files in. Select the directory and the file
 you would like to delete. Make sure you don't delete any files relevant
 to the page.
 

  

                          THE ASSIGN LINKS MODULE     


 The ASSIGN LINKS MODULE is where you can store links that can later
 be accessed from either the @{"PARAGRAPH MODULE" link "paragraph" 78} or the @{"LINKED LIST MODULE" link "List" 134}.  
 To store a link, you  must first select a @{"EXTERNAL FILE" link "Media" 88} or an 
 @{"INTERNET LINK" link "Media" 92} in the MEDIA MODULE'S main menu. 

 Once you have done this, select STORE LINK.

 When the ASSIGN LINKS MODULE'S screen opens, click on any of the
 Link buttons (1 thru 10). 

 A popup menu will appear requesting you to select the type of file you 
 are linking to. If GRAPHIC or AUDIO is selected the associated file 
 will be stored with the link. This is usually the case when the 
 operation is connected with a external file.  

 If TEXT is selected, no media file's will be stored. Use this option
 when selecting an Internet link.
  






  
    
  @{"Return" link "Media" 0}
@endnode

@node "notes" "Do's and Don'ts"
    
   
                       PAGEMONSTER DO'S AND DON'TS



 We will assume that you have successfully installed PageMonster, and that
you are about to enter PageMonster.  We also assume that you are somewhat
familiar with the Amiga Operating system.  If you are a new Amiga user, you
should become familiar with the operating system, file structure,  file
naming, and last but not least, true multi-tasking.

 There are certain rules that must be adhered to in order for PageMonster
 to function correctly.


   1. While in the PageMonster environment allow the
      PageMonster to control the other applications.  PageMonster will
      run the other applications, but you must exit each application to 
      return to PageMonster.  

   2. If for some reason you need to get to an application unrelated to 
      the PageMonster and you do not wish to exit PageMonster, then use 
      the "Left Amiga key plus the 'm' or 'n' key combinations to get to
      and from Workbench.

   3. Any screen that has a CODE WINDOW can be edited just by left mouse
      clicking on the CODE WINDOW.  PageMonster will call up the 
      @{"configured text editor" link "Config" 0} and you can manually edit the code.  
      The CODE WINDOW is a design feature of PageMonster.  When PageMonster
      builds the HTML code, you are shown this code through the 
      CODE WINDOW.
      Eventually you will understand HTML and its structured language. 
      Where tags should be inserted and what the tags will be learned, 
      do to the CODE WINDOW feedback.  

   4. External applications are accessed by PageMonster through the CLI.  
      In some  cases, PageMonster needs the application to open a 
      particular file, so that an option  must be entered into the 
      configuration along with the path to the application.  
      For example: if you are using DeluxePaintV® you must add an option
      of -f after the path name on the CONFIGURATION SCREEN before saving 
      the settings.

   5. The BACKUP feature on the MAIN SCREEN is a powerful multi-level
      backup  system.  Please read the documentation on the MAIN SCREEN 
      regarding the @{"BACKUP" link "MMenu" 124}  feature.

   6. Initially, the voice option should help to prompt you through
      PageMonster the first  few times.  After you become comfortable 
      with PageMonster you can leave the SPEECH option off.  When 
      returning to the CONFIGURATION SCREEN,  the SPEECH  option 
      automatically shuts off.

   7. When dealing with text fields in PageMonster, It is important to
      remember to  press the return key.  Failure to select the return 
      key will cause PageMonster to not  add the text to the code window.

   8. The best way to utilize the LOAD ASCII function is to create a number
      of separate ascii files using a text editor such as Ed.  Ed can be 
      run by opening a shell window and typing something like ed 
      ram:mytext.txt. Loaded the files one after another using APPEND under
      the LOAD ASCII function.  The files will appear as separate
      paragraphs when viewed in your web browser.

   9. PageMonster assembles Web Page information in it's own proprietary
      structure  which in many cases means that your original file names
      are changed to fit into PageMonster's design structure. If 
      PageMonster has made an incorrect assumption you may have to 
      manually correct this error and rename the file.


  @{"Return to Main Index" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Additions" "Additions"




                               ADDED FEATURES


 The new features that were added to Pagemonster just before the final
 release are as follows:

 IN THE CONFIGURATION SCREEN:

   AMIGAGUIDE - You may now select the location of your amigaguide
                viewer. Just select the AMIGAGUIDE button in the
                CONFIGURATION SCREEN and then the full pathname
                to where the viewer exists on your system.

                The Default is Sys:utilities/MultiView

 IN THE TITLE MODULE:

 You are now allowed to add comments to your web pages as well as
 utilize the CLIENT PULL TAG recognized by Netscape, Explorer,
 and the latest upgrade of Ibrowse. Features added to the TITLE
 MODULE are as follows:  

   AUTHOR - Enter your name in this field. It will be displayed
            as a comment in the HTML source but will not be visible
            when source is read by the web browser.

  COMMENT - Enter any comments you would like to be read when the HTML
            source is viewed, such as notes about page construction,
            etc... Comments will not be visable when source is displayed
            by the web browser.


      URL - Enter in the address to the web page or file you would like
            the browser to autoload after the specified amount of time.

            This tag will be added when the CLIENT PULL switch is set to
            ON. The default for amount of time before loading is 10 
            seconds.

            If you select the URL button, a file requestor will appear
            asking you for a file to pull this may be any type of
            external file that your web browser is configured to view
            such as a picture, anim, song module, quicktime movie, etc.. 
            
            Make sure you select the approriate extension for the file
            being loaded. If the file already has an extension, select
            NONE in the pop up menu.

            Note: This feature only works with Ibrowse 1.1 and above
                  and  will not work with the current version of AWEB.

                  It is quite common to Netscape or Internet Explorer
                  however, and will work for people viewing your page
                  with these browsers.


 IN THE PARAGRAPH MODULE:

   Two new features were added to the PARAGRAH MODULE. They are as
   follows:

   HEADER - You may now add header tags to any of the text fields in 
            the PARAGRAH MODULE while the line buttons are selected.

    COLOR - You may now add color to individual lines of text while
            the line buttons are selected.

            Note: You can change the Hex values for these colors by 
                  editing the arexx script called var.rexx located
                  in the Pagemonster:SCRIPT/ directory.

                  WARNING: BE CAREFULL fooling around with this script
                  could mess up Pagemonster's operation. Not suggested
                  if you have no knowledge of Hex values or arexx. 


  
 SPECIAL THANKS:

       Special thanks goes out to Tim Favro of Dark City Productions
       for suggesting much of the above additions.

       You may view his website at:

                       http://www.blarg.net/~darkman 
                 


                    
                     

@endnode

